parative Politics -- tReparative Pedagogies -- tConclusion -- tAfterword -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBringing together the perspectives of researchers, policy makers, activists, educators and practitioners, this book critically interrogates the Western-centric assumptions underpinning education and development agendas and the colonial legacies of violence they often uphold. The book considers the crucial connection between the idea of sustainable futures and the demand to decolonise education. Containing an innovative mixture of text, stories and poetry, it explores how decolonised futures can be conceived and enacted, offering theoretical and practical examples, including from practice in educational and cultural organisations. In doing so, the book highlights education’s potential role in facilitating processes of reparative justice that can contribute to decolonised futures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEducationxAims and objectives. 0aEducational change. 7aEDUCATION / Comparative.2bisacsh1 aArturo Cortez Ochoa, Artemio, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBirdi, Alvin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlowach, Terra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHicks-Beresford, Tanisha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoppers, Catherine A. Odora, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHutchinson, Yvette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHutchinson, Yvette, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMitchell, Rafael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMyers, Kevin, econtributor.4c